  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "55. The children of Solomon's servants—either the strangers that monarch enlisted in the building of the temple, or those who lived in his palace, which was deemed a high honor.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "The children of Solomon’s servants; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " either of those strangers and proselytes whom Solomon used in the building of the temple, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:21",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 9:21",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to the service of which, as some add, he devoted them, as there should be occasion hereafter; or others who had lived in Solomon’s family, and after his death called themselves and their families by that name, as esteeming it, a great honour to them that they had been servants to so great a prince. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
